Whoops.  I thought the private message example included a direct message from the server back to the client.  

```javascript
var io = require('socket.io')();
io.on('connection', function(socket){
  socket.emit('an event', { some: 'data' });
});
```

This is something that is missing.  There needs to be an equivalent `socket_emit` method like the `emit` method with the ability to register a callback.

The desire is to avoid the broadcast and client side filtering of any sensitive info via socket.io.

There could also be a discussion on where the per socket handlers should be managed.  Should the python application manage that or will the framework manage it for the developer?

It would be nice if the framework assisted with that (provided an interface).  If memory management becomes an issue, the application is free roll their own and not to utilize the frameworks functionality.

My use of python-socketio has been filtered by the Flask-SocketIO library. It appears the Flask-SocketIO library does not communicate all the handler arguments python-socketio is passing such as SID. 
  * https://github.com/miguelgrinberg/Flask-SocketIO/blob/v2.6.2/flask_socketio/__init__.py#L214-L217

