@scottpurdy discussed with @mrcslws and we both agree that the best way to approach the issue is not to change how we are serializing, but rather change how we keep track of segments in connections.py.  Right now a segment is just an integer determined by the order it was created. This differs from the C++ implementation which uses a struct that contains a similar id for a segment.  If we make this change, the serialization would not mess up the numbering of these segments as before. The questions I have are:
1. Is this an acceptable resolution in your eyes
2. If so should this be included in this PR or a separate one?

@wintersteiger I think there are only two different errors reported here

* Nullptr dereference when calling ``Z3_del_context()`` when Clang is compiling with OpenMP support.

* Heap use after free where something allocated in the ``prove_example2()`` function and then at some point it is freed (it is unclear exactly when from the stacktrace) and then read when doing ``bitvector_example2()``. What is really unclear to me is how ``prove_example2()`` and ``bitvector_example2()`` can effect each other given that they are using different ``Z3_context`` objects.
I tried changing ``test_capi.c`` to only call those two functions (preserving call order) and under a gcc or Clang AddressSanitized build the ``S_ASSERT(idx < m_size)`` (``../src/sat/sat_clause.h:59``) fails but under a non-sanitizied gcc build it does not and under a non-sanitized clang build it segfaults (tries to dereference a nullptr in ``../src/util/memory_manager.cpp:265``.

It looks like you're using the idea at https://gcc.gnu.org/onlinedocs/gcc/Zero-Length.html

A quick test of a sanitized build of this simple test program seems to suggest AddressSanitizer is fine with this sort of zero-length element of an array (it doesn't report any problems)

```c++
#include <inttypes.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct line {
 int length;
 char contents[0];
};

int main() {
	printf("sizeof(int) = %d\n", sizeof(int)); // 4
	printf("sizeof(line) = %d\n", sizeof(line)); // 4
	printf("sizeof(line.contents) = %d\n", sizeof(line::contents)); // 0
  line a;
  printf("addr(a) = 0x%" PRIxPTR  "\n", &a);
  printf("addr(a.length) = 0x%" PRIxPTR  "\n", &(a.length));
  printf("addr(a.contents) = 0x%" PRIxPTR  "\n", &(a.contents));

  unsigned this_length = 4;
	struct line *thisLine = (struct line *) malloc (sizeof (struct line) + this_length);
	thisLine->length = this_length;

  // Fill buffer.
  for (unsigned index = 0; index < thisLine->length ; ++index) {
    thisLine->contents[index] = 'X';
  }

  free(thisLine);
	return 0;
}
```

However it's not clear to me how you are doing allocation of these ``clause`` objects. It looks like the ``clause_allocator`` is used for this. It's doing some odd (but probably clever) things with an alignment mask. I'm a bit out of my depth here. One thought is that doing a sanitized build may be changing the way memory is laid out and breaking some implicit assumption you have in your code somewhere.

Given that you are an expert on the code my suggestion would be to try doing AddressSanitized builds on your machine and see if you can reproduce.

